NEXTDC Ltd | Asia Pacific
Our positive NXT investment thesis confirmed... as strong outlook + capital partners risk funding concerns
NEXTDC Ltd (NXT.AX) Price Target
Strengthens our thesis Impact to our thesis
In- line Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision higher Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

FY25 results in line. Industry demand for DC capacity keeps rising. NXT's list of investment opportunities is expanding... but how to fund them all? Friday it announced: 1) an increase in bank debt; 2) the introduction of capital partners for certain sites. We view this as positive news - keep OW.

Billing ramp of 57MW in FY26/58MW in FY27 fuels upside to consensus EBITDA. JVs to target high single- digit/low double- digit RoC and 15- 20% equity IRRs. Tokyo announced and advisors appointed for \(54 + 57 = 850MW\) Growth in data volume and cloud migration, plus the rapid adoption of AI technology, are driving upside surprise in both Australian and global DC demand.
We explored how NXT could work with capital partners in our 15 Sep 24 report.

Of course, every transaction will be unique/bespoke, but we estimate that NXT and capital partners can achieve 15- 20% equity IRRs and work best for DC developments with certain characteristics - large in size with significant development costs, also with single or small number of tenants, with high credit standings and signing long- term deals with the DC operator (i.e., 10- 15 years).

Remain Ow, lift our base case value/PT to A\\$20.50/share, upside of \(\sim 25\%\) : We expect NXT shares will hold their premium valuation multiple vs. Australian and US listed DC peers ... thanks to the company's significantly larger development pipeline and thus significantly higher relative growth rates. We see NXT in a "sweet spot" over the next 2- 3 years with a sequence of new sites opening + contracted utilisation wins - and based on today's news, the funding concerns will be de- risked.
MORGAN STANLEY AUSTRALIA LIMITED+
Andrew McLeod Equity Analyst
NEXTDC Ltd (NXT.AX, NXT AU)
Australia Media, Internet and Technology | Australia

After our review of NXT's FY25 results + outlook (August 29, 2025), we have increased conviction in our positive investment thesis – we keep OW and lift our PT to A \(20.50 / share: In summary, we forecast a significant increase in the earnings and intrinsic value of NXT's portfolio of DCs. The most significant news on Friday was NXT updating on how it plans to fund its significant development pipeline – including bringing in capital partners and further use of debt. In our view, this has reduced the probability of any additional equity raising being required in the next 12 months.
The three key points to our thesis:

- Structural growth – globally, data center operators are benefiting from two major secular drivers: digital transformation and cloud computing. It is the same in Australia. Most benefited from an additional tailwind of higher enterprise and government spending during Covid because of greater WFH and digital take-up. We estimate the overall Australian data center industry to grow from 1275MW today to 3200MW by 2030e. 
- NXT generates meaningful and growing FCF from the mature DCs in its portfolio ... and has the opportunity to reinvest and recycle its capital into new projects and thus drive higher long-term attractive and sustainable returns. NXT is well established in its home market of Australia, with +1,500 enterprise relationships and a strong execution track record. As NXT outlined during its FY25 investor call, the pipeline of opportunities to invest further capital is strong, in Australia and Asia. In addition, the hyperscale market represents a still significant opportunity for NXT, both in Australia, and in future across Asia. 
- NXT's equity valuation is attractive vs. Australian and global DC peers, when adjusted for significantly higher growth rates ... trading on \(\sim 45x\) FY26e EV/EBITDA with a five-year EBITDA CAGR of \(\sim 25\%\) , but we highlight that global peers have significantly lower forecast five-year revenue CAGR of \(\sim 10\%\) vs. NXT's \(\sim 25\%\) . Also, by FY29E (when NXT's cash flows from international come online), based on consensus estimates, NXT shows a reduced premium ... down from \(50\%\) (based on FY26E) ... to only \(\sim 10\%\) .

Positive long- term structural industry tailwinds

Long- term positive structural industry tailwinds for data centres have accelerated with rising AI investment, which is stimulating increased customer demand, spurring NXT's increased investment and build- out. JV strategy de- risks funding concerns. NXT has a track- record of successfully executing high- quality DC developments and also operating with high sustained EBITDA margins. Business model is scalable, with structural drivers and positive network effects. NXT's first moves into international DC markets (NZ, Malaysia, Thailand) bring higher risk/return, but with track record and annuity model, should generate strong earnings and still attractive ROIC. Positives are not fully priced in.

Faster connection + higher landbank value (A\)8/sh) + higher price outcomes: Essentially, the new data centres (DCs) have a faster ramp- up. This means that accelerated rollout and sale of new capacity lead to bull case FY26E EBITDA of \(\sim A\) 285mn, which is \(30\%\) above our base case. International construction is completed on time and on budget, with favorable surprise on ROIC generated. New International markets open up for NXT investment, with similarly positive returns achievable.

Continuing structural growth in demand for NXT's DCs; new DCs/expanded capacity under construction completed on time and on budget. We forecast EBITDA CAGR of \(\sim 25\%\) over the next three years with EBITDA margin of \(50\%\) in FY27E. Also attributes A\)5.5/sh for NXT landbank of 560MW.

Lower demand for DCs + higher energy costs + rising competition impacts. Execution issues, excess capacity or demand softness bring performance below expectations, primarily visible in MW sold. In this scenario, we factor in FY26E EBITDA of \(\sim A\) 180mn, which is \(25\%\) below our base case scenario, with a concurrent de- rating owing to lower growth rates. International expansion plans disappoint vs. investor expectations - construction cost overruns and lower prices.

- Ongoing positive hyperscale engagement- Successful Asian expansion - on time and on budget- Stable competition levels- Securing additional favourable sites for Australian DC portfolio- Securing additional growth capital options on favourable terms
